    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-18T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-18T03:00:00-05:00" n="76"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d76">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/1345: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-18T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 18, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 18—9:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>121. Reference Department’s 67, March 6, 6 p.m.<note n="63" xml:id="d76fn63">See
                        footnote 59, <ref target="#pg_75">p. 75</ref>.</note> Following from
                    American Consul General at Shanghai: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“March 16, noon. Referring to my telegram March 9, 10 a.m. Beaumont
                            unable secure Japanese adoption of the draft contained in <pb
                                facs="0191" n="79" xml:id="pg_79"/> Legation’s instruction December
                            22, 1934. Will the Legation approve my discussing the matter with Consul
                            General Ishii as a last effort to secure adoption of draft proposed as
                            part of the defense scheme. If approved and discussion unsuccessful I
                            consider the other alternative is that Beaumont advise others interested
                            that his interpretation of the particular paragraph is in accordance
                            with the Department’s draft.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>In view of the above the Legation does not desire to instruct Cunningham before
                    receiving the Department’s instructions in this connection.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
